'''David Goldie''' (1842 – 8 June 1926) was the [[Mayor of Auckland City]] from 1898 to 1901 and a [[Member of Parliament]] in New Zealand.

==Biography==

===Early life===
Born in [[Hobart]], [[Tasmania]], in 1842, Goldie emigrated to New Zealand in 1863.<ref name="NZH obit">{{cite news | url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=NZH19260609.2.101 | title=A life of service | date=9 June 1926 | work=New Zealand Herald | accessdate=1 November 2014 | page=14 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://portal.archives.tas.gov.au/menu.aspx?detail=1&type=P&id=141152 |title=Goldie, David |date=December 2011 |website= |publisher=Tasmanian Government |accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref> He was a prominent timber merchant, and a strict Primitive Methodist who resigned as Mayor of Auckland rather than toast the visiting [[George V|Duke and Duchess of Cornwall and York]] with alcohol. He was replaced as mayor for the jubilee year by the ''Father of Auckland'', Sir [[John Logan Campbell (politician)|John Logan Campbell]].

He was the father of artist [[C. F. Goldie]].

===Parliamentary career===
{{NZ parlbox header|nolist=true|align=left}}
{{NZ parlbox
 |start      = {{By-election link year|Auckland West|1879}}
 |end        = 
 |term       = 6th
 |electorate = [[Auckland West]]
 |party      = Independent (politician)
}}
{{NZ parlbox break}}
{{NZ parlbox
 |start      = {{NZ election link year|1887}}
 |end        = 1890
 |term       = 10th
 |electorate = Auckland West
 |party      = Independent (politician)
}}
{{NZ parlbox
 |start      = {{NZ election link year|1890}}
 |end        = 1891
 |term       = 11th
 |electorate = {{NZ electorate link|Newton}}
 |party      = New Zealand Liberal Party
}}
{{NZ parlbox footer}}
Goldie contested the [[Auckland West]] electorate in a [[Auckland West by-election, 1879|by-election on 4 March 1879]]. The by-election was caused by the resignation of [[Patrick Dignan]], who also stood in this contest. Dignan and Goldie received 261 and 776 votes, respectively, and with a majority of 515 votes, Goldie was declared elected.<ref>{{cite news|title=Auckland|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=EP18790305.2.16.4|accessdate=20 September 2011|newspaper=Evening Post|volume=XVII |issue=360 |date=5 March 1879|page=2}}</ref>  He served until the dissolution of parliament on 15 August of that year.<ref name=Scholefield>{{cite book
 |last= Scholefield
 |first= Guy
 |title= New Zealand Parliamentary Record, 1840–1949
 |authorlink=Guy Scholefield
 |edition=3rd
 |origyear= First ed. published 1913
 |year= 1950
 |page=109
 |publisher= Govt. Printer
 |location= Wellington
}}</ref>

Goldie represented the Auckland West electorate again from [[New Zealand general election, 1887|1887]] to [[New Zealand general election, 1890|1890]]. He then represented the [[Newton (New Zealand electorate)|Newton electorate]] from [[New Zealand general election, 1890|1890]] to 1891 as a [[New Zealand Liberal Party|Liberal]] MP, when he resigned.<ref name=Scholefield/>

===Death===
He died at his home in Auckland on 8 June 1926 and was buried at Purewa Cemetery.<ref name="NZH obit"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.purewa.co.nz/details.asp?id=36081&type=Burial |title=Burial & cremation details |date= |website= |publisher=Purewa Cemetery and Crematorium |accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref>

